President Bill Clinton and Joao Havelange, head  of the International Federation of Football Association (FIFA), met briefly  early Tuesday.
In a 15-minute get-together that also included Alan Rothenberg, chairman  of World Cup USA 1994, Clinton thanked Havelange for bringing the quadrennial  sport event to the United States, according to a statement issued by the White  House.
The men also discussed "the building enthusiasm" in the United States for  the four-week event, according to the statement.
The US president said he was looking forward to participating in the  opening ceremonies on June 17 in Chicago.
